Wyclif replies that, as regards Euclid⁷s definition of the angle — the meeting of two lines — this is merely a genetic, not an essential definition. Euclid indeed says what causes an angle; but that is not the angle itself. As to the rest, the answer is ready: Euc'lid’s theory con- cerns only sensible angles, not such as are found amongst points which touch; such, for instance, as form triangles which have sides only two points long, and of which the apex is an angle which cannot be bisected7 &c. —— All this cannot be imagined, and should, therefore, be denied from a merely geometrica] point of view (52, 53).
